{
  "style": "APA",
  "texts": [
    "Today's uncurated, internet-derived datasets commonly contain numerous anomalous instances (Pleiss et al., 2020).",
    "These anomalies can arise from multiple potential sources.",
    "For example, training data anomalies may have a natural cause such as distribution shift (Rousseeuw & Leroy, 1987; Yang et al., 2021), measurement error, or nonrepresentative samples drawn from the tail of the data distribution (Huber, 1981; Feldman, 2020b; Jiang et al., 2021).",
    "Anomalous training instances also occur due to human or algorithmic labeling errors-even on well-known, highly-curated datasets (Ekambaram et al., 2017).",
    "Malicious adversaries can insert anomalous poison instances into the training data with the goal of manipulating specific model predictions (Biggio et al., 2012; Chen et al., 2017; Shafahi et al., 2018; Hammoudeh & Lowd, 2023)."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
